Overview

HD 129445 is a star with 0.99 times the mass of the Sun, and NaN times its radius. It is located 219.96 light years away from the solar system.

HD 129445 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 129445 system


HD 129445 b

HD 129445 b was discovered by the Las Campanas Observatory observatory, in 2010-03, using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 2.90 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 129445 b is 508.800 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HD 129445 b is 13.500 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HD 129445 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
